A chieftain of the All Progressives Congress (APC), Eze Chukwuemeka Eze, has faulted the call by Rivers State governor, Nyesom Ezenwo Wike, on the APC national chairman, Adams Oshiohmole to resign from office. Wike had at the wake of the Supreme Court judgement on Bayelsa State governorship tussle, demanded Oshiohmole’s resignation for calling to stop the inauguration of Senator Douye Diri as governor of Bayelsa State. Eze, in a statement made available to LEADERSHIP in Port Harcourt yesterday, wondered if the Rivers State governor had already joined the APC to warrant his call for the resignation of its national chairman. He said: “I wonder if Wike has already joined APC to warrant him asking Comrade Adams Oshiomhole, the National Chairman to resign his position. “What is the concern of Governor Wike if the National Chairman of APC is performing or not performing to warrant Wike to ask him to resign his position if he is not threatened with the continued stay of Oshiomhole as the National Chairman of APC? “Unfortunately for the Rivers governor, he has found out very late that the plot to hijack the APC structure in Rivers State through Aguma has failed woefully as the party will be better and better without him.” The APC chieftain accused the governor of working to undermine the personality of Oshiohmole for refusing to install a two-time member of the House of Representatives, Hon. Igo Aguma, as chairman of the party  in the state, so as to pave way for Wike’s defection to the party. Eze, who is former National Publicity Secretary of the defunt new Peoples Democratic Party (PDP), also accused the governor of working clandestinely to frustrate moves to restore peace within the Rivers APC. He called on Aguma and those behind him to let the Rivers APC be, stressing that no amount of scheming will allow the illegal entry of Wike into the party.  